## Kubernetes Deployment

### Prerequisites

- Kubernetes 1.26+ cluster
- kubectl with cluster access
- Helm 3.x
- NVIDIA GPU Operator (for GPU support)

### Helm Deployment (Recommended)

```bash
# Navigate to chart directory
cd deploy/helm/kgwe

# Install PULSAR
helm install pulsar . \
  --namespace kgwe-system \
  --create-namespace \
  --values values.yaml

# Verify installation
kubectl get deployments -n kgwe-system
kubectl get pods -n kgwe-system

# Check service
kubectl get svc -n kgwe-system
```

### Manual Kubernetes Deployment

```bash
# Apply CRDs
kubectl apply -f deploy/helm/kgwe/crds/

# Apply RBAC, ConfigMap, Deployment, Service
kubectl apply -f deploy/pulsar.yaml

# Verify
kubectl get all -n kgwe-system

# View logs
kubectl logs -n kgwe-system -l app=pulsar-scheduler -f
```

### Accessing PULSAR in Cluster

```bash
# Port-forward to local machine
kubectl port-forward -n kgwe-system svc/pulsar-scheduler 8080:8080

# Access dashboard at http://localhost:8080/
```

### Configuration in Kubernetes

Edit the ConfigMap before deploying:

```bash
# Edit pulsar.yaml to customize pulsar-config ConfigMap
kubectl edit configmap pulsar-config -n kgwe-system
# Changes auto-picked up on next pod restart
```

### In-Cluster Features

When running in Kubernetes, PULSAR automatically:

- Creates `batch/v1` Jobs with `nvidia.com/gpu` resource limits
- Labels pods with `pulsar.nvidia.com/job-id`, user, priority
- Watches pod lifecycle and auto-completes/fails jobs
- Exposes `/healthz` and `/readyz` for K8s liveness/readiness probes
- Stores job history in persistent volume

### Uninstall

```bash
# Helm
helm uninstall pulsar --namespace kgwe-system

# Manual
kubectl delete -f deploy/pulsar.yaml
kubectl delete namespace kgwe-system
```

