## GPU Execution Layer

PULSAR's execution layer is what makes it a **real control plane**, not a scheduler simulator.

### Job Execution Flow

```
Scheduler admits job
   ↓
Executor launches subprocess:
   - Sets CUDA_VISIBLE_DEVICES for GPU isolation
   - Spawns worker process with GPU allocation
   - Stores PID in job record
   ↓
Worker process runs (visible in nvidia-smi):
   - Initializes GPU (torch.cuda.is_available())
   - Allocates GPU memory (torch.cuda.alloc or similar)
   - Runs compute loop (actual training/inference)
   - Periodically reports status
   ↓
Job completion or preemption:
   - Executor receives signal
   - Kills subprocess (SIGTERM → SIGKILL)
   - GPU memory released
   - Process disappears from nvidia-smi
```

### Resource Tracking

PULSAR tracks:

```
Cluster state:
  - total_gpus: 16
  - allocated_gpus: actual GPU memory used (from nvidia-smi)
  - free_gpus: calculated in real-time
  - per_team_usage: sum of all team's job processes

Job state:
  - job_id, team_id, gpu_requested, gpu_allocated
  - process_pid, memory_usage_mb
  - start_time, runtime_seconds
  - status (QUEUED → RUNNING → COMPLETED)
```

### PID Mapping

API & CLI expose PID information:

```bash
# Get job details with PID
pulsar jobs team-a
#→ job-123 | team-a | 4 GPUs | PID: 12345 | 8GB used | RUNNING

# Trace in nvidia-smi
nvidia-smi
#→ GPU 0-3: process 12345 (PULSAR worker) | 8GB | 95% utilization
```

This allows users to:

- Verify their job is actually running
- Debug resource issues
- Monitor GPU utilization live
- Correlate scheduled jobs to real processes

